textDisplay:
“You want to know how he’s choosing them don’t you?”

“I thought you might have some ideas.”

“Why should I tell you?”

“You get to see the file on this case; and there’s another reason.”

“Pray tell.”

“I thought you might be curious to see if you’re smarter than the person I’m looking for.”

“Then, by implication, you think you’re smarter than me; since you caught me.”

“No. I know I’m not smarter than you.”

“Then, how did you catch me?”

“You had disadvantages.”

“What disadvantages?”

“You’re insane.”

textDisplay: In this scene, Joker talks to Batman like an older brother - he adores him and identifies with him. Batman cloaks his true self in the shadows, but Joker puts his darkness in the spotlight for all to see his sadistic symphony. The truly evil genius and the world's greatest detective. Batman cannot solve the Riddler's riddles because he refuses to see the monster he has buried inside. The Joker knows that Batman is on the edge between retribution and bloodlust. Because of this, the Joker is the teacher and all Batman can do is listen to his psychotic professor. He is deformed and eroded from his chemical rebirth, not painted like a clown. He is not a joke, but terrifying. And Batman is the hunter, undetectable in the shadows and atop the skyline, but he is the one in fear.

textDisplay:
J: …mm. Present. Almost our anniversary, isn’t it?



B: There’s a serial killer. I want your perspective.



J: First anniversary is…paper. What makes you think I come so cheap?



B: I thought you’d be curious.



J: You think I get off on this stuff?



B: Don’t you?



J: You have pictures. Hee heee…… Ooh, this violence. It’s so baroque. He likes little puzzles, doesn’t he? So meticulous. Like he’d been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.



B: Who? Who is he?



J: He’s a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The mayor, the commissioner…yeah… He’s got ambition.



B: You think his motive is political?



J: Oh no no. This is very, very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds, stolen lunch money…



B: Why is he writing to me?


J: Maybe he’s a fan of yours? Or maybe he’s got a grudge against you too. Maybe you’re the main course. Any theories?



B: Not yet.



J: Really? You’re normally so ahead of the curve. But something is different this time. This is very upsetting to you.



B: Let’s get back to him.



J: Why? You’re so much more fun!



B: I’m not here to talk about me.



J: What are you here to talk about?



B: I want to know how he thinks.



J: You know exactly how he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers! So he’s even more righteous. Aww, are you afraid he makes you look soft?



B: You’re wasting my time.



J: I’ll tell you! I’ll tell you what I really think. I think, you don’t really care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think, somewhere deep down, you’re just terrified because you’re not sure he’s wrong, huh? You think they deserved it, huh? You think they deserved it!
textOriginal:
J: …mm. Present. Almost our anniversary, isn’t it?

 

B: There’s a serial killer. I want your perspective.

 

J: First anniversary is…paper. What makes you think I come so cheap?

 

B: I thought you’d be curious.

 

J: You think I get off on this stuff?

 

B: Don’t you?

 

J: You have pictures. Hee heee…… Ooh, this violence. It’s so baroque. He likes little puzzles, doesn’t he? So meticulous. Like he’d been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.

 

B: Who? Who is he?

 

J: He’s a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The mayor, the commissioner…yeah… He’s got ambition.

 

B: You think his motive is political?

 

J: Oh no no. This is very, very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds, stolen lunch money…

 

B: Why is he writing to me?


J: Maybe he’s a fan of yours? Or maybe he’s got a grudge against you too. Maybe you’re the main course. Any theories?

 

B: Not yet.

 

J: Really? You’re normally so ahead of the curve. But something is different this time. This is very upsetting to you.

 

B: Let’s get back to him.

 

J: Why? You’re so much more fun!

 

B: I’m not here to talk about me.

 

J: What are you here to talk about?

 

B: I want to know how he thinks.

 

J: You know exactly how he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers! So he’s even more righteous. Aww, are you afraid he makes you look soft?

 

B: You’re wasting my time.

 

J: I’ll tell you! I’ll tell you what I really think. I think, you don’t really care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think, somewhere deep down, you’re just terrified because you’re not sure he’s wrong, huh? You think they deserved it, huh? You think they deserved it!

textDisplay: Impressive performance, but comes off as too try hard to be honest. It seems they were going for heath ledger joker but x10. It seems very cartoonish, which is fine if it was in a show or cartoon film. I just can't take him seriously, as this take on the joker doesn't really seem like "unpredictable, unhinged, meticioulus guy with a motive" seems more like "crazy, coocoo guy that will just laugh and stab anyone in sight." like if Leatherface had a laugh, this would be it. I don't really see why this has to be a recurring theme for on screen jokers. Arkham game joker did something similar, and it was great, but here, especially after Jared's joker, it's a long recurring trope. He looks horrendous, which is pretty cool. Like he actuall fell in a vat of acid, I like that cosmetic choice. Idk, imo it's just another mindless, "sooo crazy", guy nothing underneath, but of course it's literally one deleted scene, so who knows, maybe it'll be fleshed out if there's ever a sequel to this movie.

textDisplay:
Credit to Little Michael Jr.

Transcript of the Joker Deleted Scene

Joker: Oh, Hm. Fragrant. Almost our anniversary, isn't it?

Batman: There’s a serial killer. I want your perspective.

Joker: First anniversary is papers. What makes you think I come so cheap?

Batman: I thought you’d be curious.

Joker: You think I get off on this stuff?

Batman: Don’t you?

Joker: You have pictures? [Laughs] Oooh. His violence… It’s so Baroque. Ooh, he likes little puzzles, doesn’t he? So meticulous. Like he had been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.

Batman: Who? Who is he?

Joker: He’s a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The Mayor, the Commissioner. Yeah. He’s got ambition.

Batman: You think his motive is political?

Joker: Oh no, no, no. This is very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds, stolen lunch money.

Batman: Why's he writing to me?

Joker: Maybe he's a fan of yours? Or maybe he's got a grudge against you too. Maybe you're the main course. Any theories?

Batman: Not yet.

Joker: Really? You’re normally so ahead of the curve. But something is different this time. This is very upsetting to you.

Batman: Let’s get back to him.

Joker: Why? You are so much more fun.

Batman: I’m not here to talk about me.

Joker: What are you here to talk about?

Batman: I want to know how he thinks.

Joker: You know exactly what he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers, huh? 'Cept he's even more righteous. Aww, you afraid he makes you look soft? [Laughs]

Batman: You’re wasting my time.

Joker: [Laughs] Okay, okay! I'll tell you what I really think. I think you don't really care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think somewhere, deep down, you're just terrified. 'Cause you're not sure he's wrong, huh? You think they deserved it, huh? You think they deserved it! [Laughs]

textDisplay:
I think people are really only hating on this film because of the whole "Oh it's a DC movie- it's not as good as Marvel so there is nothing good about it" concept that way too many people hold. Because a lot of the complaints are just stupid or if you analyzed the film whatsoever would make sense- and anyone who says you shouldn't need to analyze a film to find it enjoyable only like kids movies.
1. People complain about how Catwoman didn't play a bigger part. Of course she didn't, she wasn't the main focus. The only reason she was there was to add one of Batman's several love interests into the film to flesh out the world more. And of course the chemistry wasn't overly worked on- once again, the chemistry wasn't apart of the film. Hell, she's not even Catwomen yet and the two literally just met. This wasn't a romance movie.
2. People said it was too long. Okay yeah, it was a long movie, but the purpose was to once again start to map out the world. We were introduced to a lot of minor characters because just by introducing them it gives a certain excitement towards people who enjoy the Batman comics. I mean, some of the characters introduced are characters that haven't had a canon screen appearance in years. So for long time fans to be able to see that person in a film by DC, it gives a world of possibilities for other upcoming movies. It makes it so it is hard to guess what the next movie is going to be about, which excites people.
3. People claim there were too many plots going on at once. And well, that's total bullshit. There was only really one plot: The Riddler thinks Batman is like him and wants to punish Gotham, but Batman isn't like him and saves Gotham instead. The only other possible thing that could be considered a plot was the whole romance between Selina and Batman, but once again that wasn't the focus of the film. Everything else in the movie was basically side quests you needed to take to get context on what the plot was. Anyone who missed this either wasn't paying attention to the movie or wasn't using critical thinking.

textDisplay: On one hand this scene is very effective given the theme of the movie, on the other I can totally see why it was cut. For one, this really feels like an imitation of Heath Ledger's joker, which I love but we've had that version and Ledger already portrayed it perfectly. And also, this really isn't that necessary for the plot; I got that batman was conflicted over feeling like the riddler's victims deserved it without it needing to be said outright. We don't really find out any new information here and the movie is already three hours, so it makes sense this is the scene they'd cut.

textDisplay: Just got back from watching The Batman a second time. It’s honestly hard to tell where this scene could have been fitted in. It’s not just a pacing problem, but it also seems like it steps away from the story for a bit. The movie is already very long as it is and I can imagine Matt Reeves would also agree that this scene would have diminished the menacing nature of the other villains. I think it’s a better sequel set up than what we got indeed, but it’s also somewhat useless in the sense that it is a reiterating of the themes already being expressed and it may be somewhat be a little bit on the nose too, maybe not. textDisplay:
Such a fantastic scene but it could not have made the final cut because it took the spotlight away from Paul Dano's Riddler and it also would have undermined their efforts to make this version of Batman more closer to being the World's Greatest Detective than he's ever been before. The Joker gives Batman strong advice on who the Riddler is and therefore he is effectively being given the answers rather than working it out for himself like he does in the theatrical cut.

I understand why people are saying that the Joker has been portrayed enough in films and that they should be giving other villains a chance, but the Joker is Batman's arch-enemy and it would be remiss of them not to include him in any future films in this Batman Universe.

This take on the Joker looks creepy as hell and is a crazed mixture of psychotic and pure genius. I feel he is still a fresh enough take on the character from just this one scene to have him involved against this Batman at some point. It will be interesting to see where they go with the story they are telling us in any future films.
textOriginal:

The Joker gives Batman strong advice on who the Riddler is and therefore he is effectively being given the answers rather than working it out for himself like he does in the theatrical cut.

I understand why people are saying that the Joker has been portrayed enough in films and that they should be giving other villains a chance, but the Joker is Batman's arch-enemy and it would be remiss of them not to include him in any future films in this Batman Universe.

This take on the Joker looks creepy as hell and is a crazed mixture of psychotic and pure genius. I feel he is still a fresh enough take on the character from just this one scene to have him involved against this Batman at some point. It will be interesting to see where they go with the story they are telling us in any future films.

textDisplay: After getting past the amazing artistry of this scene — the cinematography, the performances, the music, the makeup, the lighting — I've just realized that Joker's probably right. Riddler is revealing to the city that the mayor, the police commissioner, the district attorney, basically their entire government, is completely corrupt, controlled by a mob boss who holds onto power through murder and intimidation. If Batman believes in working outside the law to fight crime, how can he not think, on some level, that what Riddler is doing is serving justice? And once you start tearing at that thread, you realize that if Riddler's really just an angry manchild looking for a justification that makes his primal desire to hurt people seem like the right thing to do, how inaccurate can that be as a description of Batman himself?
textOriginal: After getting past the amazing artistry of this scene — the cinematography, the performances, the music, the makeup, the lighting — I've just realized that Joker's probably right. Riddler is revealing to the city that the mayor, the police commissioner, the district attorney, basically their entire government, is completely corrupt, controlled by a mob boss who holds onto power through murder and intimidation. If Batman believes in working outside the law to fight crime, how can he not think, on some level, that what Riddler is doing is serving justice? And once you start tearing at that thread, you realize that if Riddler's really just an angry manchild looking for a justification that makes his primal desire to hurt people seem like the right thing to do, how inaccurate can that be as a description of Batman himself?

textDisplay: What a good amount of you aren’t seeming to understand (Why? I don’t know but then again I don’t like being spoonfed with my film watching) is that Bruce is already feeling conflicted on a number of things. He knows these victims aren’t good people. At the same time he feels the need to deliver justice and vengeance on his own terms. Not Riddler’s. He goes to Joker hoping that it’s simply in his head and that he’s indeed seeing things clearly but Joker flawlessly points out Bruce’s insecurities and shows him that he’s not yet the beacon of light he is by the end of the film. Bruce didn’t go to Joker strictly for answers about Riddler he went to him for answers about himself. Hence why he got so defensive when the conversation turned on him. Joker condescended him about being ahead of the curve and knowing exactly who Riddler is. Bruce put on a front but ultimately he left with even more conflict than he had walked in with. Joker left him with those final words hammering it home. This scene should have been in the film!

textDisplay:
Transcript of the Joker Deleted Scene

Joker: Fragrant

Batman: There’s a serial killer. I want your perspective.

Joker: First anniversary is papers. What makes you think I come so cheap?

Batman: I thought you’d be curious.

Joker: You think I get off on this stuff?

Batman: Don’t you?

Joker: You have pictures? [Laughs] Oooh. His violence… It’s so Baroque. Ooh, he likes little puzzles, doesn’t he? So meticulous. Like he had been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.

Batman: Who? Who is he?

Joker: He’s a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The Mayor, the Commissioner. Yeah. He’s got ambition.

Batman: You think his motive is political?

Joker: Oh no, no, no. This is very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds, stolen lunch money.

Batman: Why's he writing to me?

Joker: Maybe he's a fan of yours? Or maybe he's got a grudge against you too. Maybe you're the main course. Any theories?

Batman: Not yet.

Joker: Really? You’re normally so ahead of the curve. But something is different this time. This is very upsetting to you.

Batman: Let’s get back to him.

Joker: Why? You are so much more fun.

Batman: I’m not here to talk about me.

Joker: What are you here to talk about?

Batman: I want to know how he thinks.

Joker: You know exactly what he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers, huh? 'Cept he's even more righteous. Aww, you afraid he makes you look soft? [Laughs]

Batman: You’re wasting my time.

Joker: [Laughs] Okay, okay! I'll tell you what I really think. I think you don't reall care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think somewhere, deep down, you're just terrified. 'Cause you're not sure he's wrong, huh? You think they deserved it, huh? You think they deserved it! [Laughs]

textDisplay:
Eh... hes too common sounding. Sounds like a ledger wannabe and some wise guy snide like new yorker voice. Hes close but not quite right. They keep trying to one up the demented nature ledger epitomized. While i think joker now needs more of a solidity like hannibal lecter. Something that isnt just unhinging for shock and awe but a colder calculation and solid resolve to joker. Let the presence of joke speak for itself with a hint of his unhinging. That this asylum wont get to him until bats starts to leave. It just doesnt represent the mind of a madness that counter parts batman here but a clearly lunatic mind you cant see organizing gotham’s villains. Hes too crazy but not balanced with the sanity joker counter intuitively possesses . As any asylum patient, you’d expect him to just blend it to any padded room ... He doesnt have that underlying contemplative spark you get from a villain like moriarty, or green goblin in now way home(where a cure can be acquired for his madness, hes just crookedly insane), or lector, or jeckel and hyde, doctor frankenstein,... minds that really truly epitomize the stability of true madness with depth that keeps the character terrifying to an emotional level. Here you just expect it.

The psychological depth of ledger’s character. Had shock and awe but contemplation to his serial criminality. He was chaos in organic nature without self righteousness or plain old demand. As if he needed to exist to test the truth of gotham because he was a result of gotham. Its mankind’s madness looking into a mirror of itself. Thats when the joker really shines beyond his classic cultural iconic fruitiness.

Joker should be less willing to fall into the flamboyant madness of a padded room. He needs to be trying to hold it all together. But a madness of cause and effect. Batman is his cause. Joker’s madness is the effect.

textDisplay:
Those who got stuck with Ledger, or Nicholson or Joaquin whoever… Heath made an incredible performance But his character is… meh… isn’t perfect. I liked that he wasn’t humorous, that he just ironized the humor. That instead of these weird goofy clowns in cartoons and arkham games and Tim Burton’s movies, who’s threat just isn’t believable at all, Heath’s joker was an intelligent maniac. Who behaved kinda weird and goofy but was cold minded. You could see it in his eyes…


BUT.





Barry Koeghan. In 5 minutes. Gave us. An intelligent person with a mental and physical (neural) disorder. Means he can’t control his emotions. But he isn’t goofy. He is not funny. He is serious.

Despite of his behavior and his clownesque partial appearance, He’s not a joker. He tells no joke. There’s nothing funny nor humorous about this man. This is a dangerous man.
THIS IS THE JOKER.



























































































































I don’t want a good joker.

I don’t want a cool joker.

I don’t want a great joker.





I WANT A TERRIFYING VILLAIN.


I WANT THE JOKER.

textDisplay:
It’s a good scene, almost brings to mind Hannibal Lecter and Clarice Starling, but I’m glad that it was cut, the film was long enough already and didn’t really need this little bit. We don’t really lose a lot from this removal and one could argue we actually gain from it because it would just diminish the threat of the Riddler knowing that the frickin Joker was right there. This was also probably a last minute cut given how it just looks like a clip from the movie, music and everything so they were probably working on the final cut and were looking for stuff to trim to get it under three hours.

Though it would be cool to see a whole series of Batman films and his only interaction with the Joker is just little scenes like this.

textDisplay:
Heath ledger’s performance as the joker is without a doubt one of the greatest joker performances ever. Mark Hamill‘s voice work on Batman the animated series is also exceptional.
This performance however as short as it was could very well be an extension of heath ledger‘s performance.
I can certainly understand why it was cut from the Batman movie I just hope they return to this in a sequel or perhaps a prequel.
For what amounts do about four minutes of screen time this joke was performance was truly unnerving, terrifying, and completely fantastic!

textDisplay: Omg he is perfect for Joker,he's only had a 5 minute scene and he's already the most accurate,Heath Ledger is overrated this scene with this Joker felt straight out of a comic book and the animated series he looks terrifying,the laugh is on point Bruce has only been there for a short amount of time and he's already getting inside his head when he said "You think they deserved it" I think this Batman needs more than one trilogy at least two,they can use other villains never seen before on screen but this Joker has to be used in one of them I would love to see them brawl it out,Bruce attempting to stop the Joker from blowing up the city and he just beats the crap out of his goons Matt Reeves has to use him in one of the sequels my gosh I would love to see this Joker go on an absolute mad one causing mayhem,this is just what you call Joker and what I love about is that Bruce has already fought him and dealt with his madness I think Matt Reeves has crazy surprises planned out for us in this Batverse they couldn't have picked a better director,cast and crew I cannot wait for more,as soon as I heard the Joker's laugh I just immediately lost it for a second and geeked out "JOKER" in my head I don't care about how many times the Joker has been used he's Bruce's main arch enemy and you can't have a live action Batman without using Joker I mean come on,it's like Spider-Man without the Green Goblin or the Flash without Reverse Flash,every hero needs they're arch enemy the main one that breaks them down to their core,I just know we're gonna see this Joker in one of the sequels there's no way they're not gonna use him all I can say is that is the Batman I've long been waiting for and it's finally here Robert Pattinson was just born to be Batman/Bruce Wayne Matt Reeves is an absolute genius

textDisplay:
----SUBTITLES----

J: Hmmm. A present. Almost our anniversary, isn’t it?
B: There’s a serial killer. I want your perspective
J: First anniversary is papers. What makes you think I come so cheap?
B: I thought you’d be curious
J: You think I get off on this stuff?
B: Don’t you?
J: You have pictures… Oooh, his violence… is so Baroque. He likes little puzzles, doesn’t he? So meticulous. Like he had been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.
B: Who? Who is he?
J: He’s a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The mayor, the commissioner. Yeah, he’s got ambition
B: You think his motive is political?
J: Oh no, no, no. This is very, very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds… stolen lunch money.
B: Why he writing to me?
J: Maybe… he’s a fan of yours? Or maybe he got a grudge against you too. Maybe you’re main course. Any theories?
B: Not yet.
J: Really? You’re normally so ahead of the curve. But something’s different this time. This is very upsetting to you.
B: Let’s get back to him
J: Why? You are so much more fun!
B: I’m not here to talk about me
J: What are you here to talk about?
B: I want to know how he thinks
J: You know exactly how he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers huh? Except he’s even more righteous.
Aww… you afraid he makes you look soft?
B: You’re wasting my time
J: Okay okay! I’ll tell you what I really think. I think you don’t really care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think somewhere deep down, you’re just terrified. Cause you’re not sure he’s wrong huh? You think they deserved it huh? You think they deserved it!
[laughter]

textDisplay:
In the immortal words of Morgan Freeman's Lucius Fox: "This.... Is wrong".

Hear me out here. 👂

This is completely - and I mean COMPLETELY - opposite of The Joker I want to see.

Sure it is evocatively lensed - but it's also tediously lame due to being so irrevocably contrived.

The Joker is not a grotesquely disfigured downs-syndromed child!

The Joker is slick, charismatic, cunning, clever and so insidiously seductive that he gaslights his own prison psychiatrists to tap into her wildest side and abandon her professional life to aid in his escape and join him in his ambitious escapades to upheeve the status quo and do it with style to spare!

__________________________________

He ought to be like this amalgam:

- Brad Pitt's Tyler Durdan from David Fincher's "Flight Club

+ Mickey Rourke in Adrian Lyne's "Nine And A Half Weeks"

+ Woody Harrison's Mickey Knox from Oliver Stone's Natural Born Killers

+ Donald Sunderland in Bernardo Bertolucci's "1900"

+ Eric Roberts in Bob Fosse's "Star 80"

+ death cult leader Charlie Manson

+ serial killer Ted Bundy

+ 90's alt rocker Perry Farrell of Jane's Addiction

+ 80's punk Billy Idol

__________________________________

His namesake quirk ought to be his uncontrollably telling tick to signal when he's at his most dangeous - an exaggeratedly excited smile and gleefully giddy chuckle.

Do I think Barry Keoghan could ever portray that? No. Never. Not ever. Stop it.

__________________________________

Since unfortunately Willem Defoe and Vincent Gallo are now both probably just too old to get mesmerizingly wiley enough - I want CLIFTON COLLINS JR. to finally bring to cinematic life the definitive portrait of The Joker! Which by sheer happenstance would nicely harken back to the latino heritage of the first actor that portrayed the character in the 60's tv series - Cesar Romero.

I see Joaquin Phoenix's "Joker" as also existing in this universe, but only as an infamous cultural touchstone reference turned adopted moniker in whose mythical 70's era incitement to riot (and subsequent escape and disappearance) fuels THE Joker to build his great cathedral of anarchy in tribute to.

__________________________________

I love Matt Reeves as a filmmaker and aside from the Arkham scene at the end, I consider his version of Gotham in "The Batman" to be the best put to screen. But his take on a potential Joker is the epitome of dreadfully ill-concieved in my opinion.

textDisplay:
I can understand that people think he understands Batman really well, but you people really give him too much credit. If he truly understood how Batman worked, he wouldn't be behind bars. He'll get some things, but he obviously can't get everything right. Batman has his quarrels, sure, but in the end, he'll always side with what he feels is right. As long as he knows people that are good like Gordon and the mayor, he'll never lose hope.

It's also smart to never answer or react to him because with every reaction and answer he gives, it gives Joker something to feed off of, as well as hints. By showing no emotion and keeping on track, Joker in the end, has to keep guessing. Nonetheless, doesn't change the fact that he got most of it right and I also applaud him for that.

textDisplay: Personally didn't like what was actually in the film from him and was already not looking forward at all to seeing this interpretation but, my mind has kinda changed just from this. Now my only issue remaining is that's it's yet another really recent take on the character that's definitely not at all needed though I think this type of role can work and be interesting to see. However, I'm just worried he takes up too much of the spotlight. I want to see new villains who haven't had a chance in live-action thus far to get one like Clay Face,  (where he's not a clay monster to fit in this world like his first appearance in Detective Comics, but just a guy with a horrible clay mask murdering people in a very Phantom of the Opera esque way and you could make him wear prosthetics to get into places changing his face with masks. Think that could really work and make for an amazing detective story), Court of Owls (probably only after 2nd or 3rd film if there is one though to have needed effect), Hush, Hatter, Firefly or even villains that could do with another take like especially Freeze or Ivy, but even Scarecrow, Two-face, Ra's/Talia and Bane again too as they haven't been abused to death and can be done differently and still feel fresh

textDisplay: By everything shown here, Barry Keoghan would make an excellent Joker. Here is my issue. There have been so many amazing incarnations of the Joker on both the small and big screen. Of all the Batman villains, the Joker has been portrayed the most often and with the most depth. Its time to give other foes that make up Batman's rogue gallery their due. It would be shame to continue focusing on one character, when the roster of criminals that Batman has encountered over his long and storied history in the comics is so rich.

textDisplay: What people never really get about Batman is the synchronicity aspect of his character. His father, Thomas Wayne, is who created these insane people, with funding unorthodox experiments on mentally disturbed people, making them worse. Batman is thus, a creation of his father's unethical practices, and consequent actions of his inability to get over his parents death. What people like the Joker and Riddler know, is that the real Batman is hiding within his darkness, shadows, each of them attempting to release that darkness to convert him. Batman is a vigilante, using violence to settle scores with an underworld even Thomas Wayne was a part of with figures like Don Falcone. Each Joker character gives us greater insight. But this Batman is by far the best in honing in on the dark of Batman, Gotham in general, and all the characters calling it home. Batman in general, is the most compelling of all of comic book characters.  I can't wait to see this version. It's more authentic and realistic, dark and edgy, with all of the lineup more compellingly portrayed.

What people like the Joker and Riddler know, is that the real Batman is hiding within his darkness, shadows, each of them attempting to release that darkness to convert him. Batman is a vigilante, using violence to settle scores with an underworld even Thomas Wayne was a part of with figures like Don Falcone. Each Joker character gives us greater insight. But this Batman is by far the best in honing in on the dark of Batman, Gotham in general, and all the characters calling it home. Batman in general, is the most compelling of all of comic book characters.  I can't wait to see this version. It's more authentic and realistic, dark and edgy, with all of the lineup more compellingly portrayed.

textDisplay: I loved this scene. textDisplay: Honestly, I don't know how to feel. I kinda hope he remains a side character, tbh. I'm over Joker being just a serial killer. Even Heath's performance, as amazing as it was, has gotten kind of old for me because for me it's kind of a symbol of Batman becoming less and less fun over the years. I loved this new movie, and I love Nolan's movies, but I would really rather have a Batman movie that feels like Arkham City. That game will always be the standard for Batman stories in my mind. It has all the comic book craziness while feeling every bit as dark (and sometimes darker) than anything we've seen in the movies.
textOriginal: Honestly, I don't know how to feel. I kinda hope he remains a side character, tbh. I'm over Joker being just a serial killer. Even Heath's performance, as amazing as it was, has gotten kind of old for me because for me it's kind of a symbol of Batman becoming less and less fun over the years. I loved this new movie, and I love Nolan's movies, but I would really rather have a Batman movie that feels like Arkham City. That game will always be the standard for Batman stories in my mind. It has all the comic book craziness while feeling every bit as dark (and sometimes darker) than anything we've seen in the movies.

textDisplay:
J: Oh. Present? Almost our anniversary, isn't it?
B: There's a serial killer. I want your perspective.
J: Our first anniversary is paper. What makes you think I come so cheap?
B: I thought you'd be curious.
J: You think I get off of this stuff?
B: Don't you?
J: You have pictures?
His violence, it's so baroque. He likes little puzzles, doesn't he? So meticulous. Like he'd been planning this his whole life. I know who he is.
B: Who? Who is he?
J: He's a nobody. Wants to be somebody. The mayor. The commissioner. He's got ambition.
B: You think his motive is political?
J: Oh no, no no no this is very very personal. He feels these people have all wronged him. Probably goes way back. Unhealed wounds, stolen lunch money.
B: Why is he writing to me?
J: Maybe he's a fan of yours?
Or maybe he's got a grudge against you too. Maybe you're the main cause? Any theories?
B: Not yet.
J: Really? You're normally so ahead of the curve.
But something is different this time. This is very upsetting to you.
B: Let's get back to him.
J: Why? You are so much more fun!
B: I'm not here to talk about me.
J: What are you here to talk about?
B: I want to know how he thinks.
J: You know exactly how he thinks. Have you read this file? You two have so much in common. Masked avengers. So he's even more righteous. You're afraid he makes you look soft.
B: You're wasting my time.
J: Okay! Can I tell you what I really think? I think you don't really care about his motives, whether he loves or hates you. I think somewhere, deep down, you're just terrified, cause you're not sure he's wrong, huh? You think they deserved it, huh? You think they deserved it!
